                <!-- Kelly Criterion -->
                <div class="formula-card">
                    <div class="formula-title">
                        <i class="fas fa-balance-scale"></i>
                        Kelly Criterion
                    </div>
                    
                    <p class="formula-explanation">
                        The Kelly Criterion determines the optimal fraction of your capital to risk per trade to maximize long-term growth. Developed by John L. Kelly Jr. at Bell Labs in 1956, it balances growth rate against risk of ruin.
                    </p>
                    
                    <div class="formula-math">
                        f* = (bp - q) / b
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="variable-list">
                        <div class="variable-item">
                            <span class="variable-symbol">f*</span>
                            <span class="variable-description">Optimal fraction of capital to risk (Kelly percentage)</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="variable-item">
                            <span class="variable-symbol">b</span>
                            <span class="variable-description">Net odds received on the bet (avg win / avg loss)</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="variable-item">
                            <span class="variable-symbol">p</span>
                            <span class="variable-description">Probability of winning (win rate as decimal)</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="variable-item">
                            <span class="variable-symbol">q</span>
                            <span class="variable-description">Probability of losing (1 - p)</span>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="example-box">
                        <div class="example-title">
                            <i class="fas fa-lightbulb me-2"></i>Example
                        </div>
                        <p style="color: #9ba1a6; margin-bottom: 0;">
                            If you have a 60% win rate with an average win of $300 and average loss of $150:<br>
                            b = 300/150 = 2, p = 0.60, q = 0.40<br>
                            f* = (2 × 0.60 - 0.40) / 2 = <strong style="color: #00ff88;">40%</strong>
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="verification-box">
                        <div class="verification-title">
                            <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i>
                            How to Verify
                        </div>
                        <p style="color: #9ba1a6; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
                            1. Open browser DevTools (F12)<br>
                            2. View source code in <code>/public/calculations.js</code><br>
                            3. Search for <code>calculateKellyCriterion()</code> function
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div style="margin-top: 1rem;">
                        <span class="reference-badge">
                            <i class="fas fa-book-open me-1"></i>
                            Fortune's Formula (Poundstone, 2005)
                        </span>
                        <span class="reference-badge">
                            <i class="fas fa-graduation-cap me-1"></i>
                            Bell System Technical Journal (1956)
                        </span>
                        <span class="reference-badge">
                            <i class="fas fa-chart-line me-1"></i>
                            Ed Thorp - Beat the Dealer
                        </span>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Fixed Percentage -->
                <div class="formula-card">
                    <div class="formula-title">
                        <i class="fas fa-percentage"></i>
                        Fixed Percentage Position Sizing
                    </div>
                    
                    <p class="formula-explanation">
                        Risk a fixed percentage of your account on each trade. Simple, conservative, and widely used by institutional traders. Automatically scales position size with account growth or drawdown.
                    </p>
                    
                    <div class="formula-math">
                        Position Size = (Account Balance × Risk%) / Risk Per Share
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="variable-list">
                        <div class="variable-item">
                            <span class="variable-symbol">Risk%</span>
                            <span class="variable-description">Percentage of account to risk (typically 1-2%)</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="variable-item">
                            <span class="variable-symbol">Risk/Share</span>
                            <span class="variable-description">Entry price - stop loss price</span>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="example-box">
                        <div class="example-title">
                            <i class="fas fa-lightbulb me-2"></i>Example
                        </div>
                        <p style="color: #9ba1a6; margin-bottom: 0;">
                            $10,000 account, 2% risk, entry at $50, stop at $48 (risk $2/share):<br>
                            Position Size = ($10,000 × 0.02) / $2 = <strong style="color: #00ff88;">100 shares</strong><br>
                            Total Position Value = 100 × $50 = <strong style="color: #00ff88;">$5,000</strong>
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div style="margin-top: 1rem;">
                        <span class="reference-badge">
                            <i class="fas fa-book-open me-1"></i>
                            Van K. Tharp - Trade Your Way to Financial Freedom
                        </span>
                        <span class="reference-badge">
                            <i class="fas fa-university me-1"></i>
                            Ryan Jones - The Trading Game
                        </span>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Risk Management Category -->
                <h2 id="risk-management" class="category-header">
                    <i class="fas fa-shield-alt me-2"></i>Risk Management
                </h2>

                <!-- Risk of Ruin -->
                <div class="formula-card">
                    <div class="formula-title">
                        <i class="fas fa-exclamation-triangle"></i>
                        Risk of Ruin
                    </div>
                    
                    <p class="formula-explanation">
                        Probability of losing your entire trading account. Critical for understanding long-term survival. Based on Ralph Vince's work in portfolio mathematics.
                    </p>
                    
                    <div class="formula-math">
                        RoR = ((1 - W) / (1 + W))^(A / U)
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="variable-list">
                        <div class="variable-item">
                            <span class="variable-symbol">RoR</span>
                            <span class="variable-description">Risk of Ruin (probability as decimal)</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="variable-item">
                            <span class="variable-symbol">W</span>
                            <span class="variable-description">Winning advantage (win rate - loss rate)</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="variable-item">
                            <span class="variable-symbol">A</span>
                            <span class="variable-description">Account size in units</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="variable-item">
                            <span class="variable-symbol">U</span>
                            <span class="variable-description">Average number of units risked per trade</span>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="verification-box">
                        <div class="verification-title">
                            <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i>
                            Implementation Note
                        </div>
                        <p style="color: #9ba1a6; margin-bottom: 0;">
                            We use Monte Carlo simulation (10,000 iterations) to calculate practical risk of ruin by simulating random trade sequences based on your win rate and average win/loss.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div style="margin-top: 1rem;">
                        <span class="reference-badge">
                            <i class="fas fa-book-open me-1"></i>
                            Ralph Vince - Portfolio Mathematics
                        </span>
                        <span class="reference-badge">
                            <i class="fas fa-chart-line me-1"></i>
                            Optimal f Theory
                        </span>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Portfolio Heat -->
                <div class="formula-card">
                    <div class="formula-title">
                        <i class="fas fa-fire"></i>
                        Portfolio Heat
                    </div>
                    
                    <p class="formula-explanation">
                        Total risk across all open positions as a percentage of account. Prevents over-leveraging by tracking cumulative exposure.
                    </p>
                    
                    <div class="formula-math">
                        Heat = Σ(Position Risk) / Account Balance × 100
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="variable-list">
                        <div class="variable-item">
                            <span class="variable-symbol">Position Risk</span>
                            <span class="variable-description">Shares × (Entry - Stop Loss)</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="variable-item">
                            <span class="variable-symbol">Σ</span>
                            <span class="variable-description">Sum of all open positions</span>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="example-box">
                        <div class="example-title">
                            <i class="fas fa-lightbulb me-2"></i>Recommended Limits
                        </div>
                        <p style="color: #9ba1a6; margin-bottom: 0;">
                            <strong style="color: #00ff88;">Conservative:</strong> 6-8% total portfolio heat<br>
                            <strong style="color: #d68b45;">Moderate:</strong> 8-12% total portfolio heat<br>
                            <strong style="color: #ff6b6b;">Aggressive:</strong> 12-15% total portfolio heat (not recommended)
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Performance Metrics Category -->
                <h2 id="performance" class="category-header">
                    <i class="fas fa-chart-line me-2"></i>Performance Metrics
                </h2>

                <!-- Trade Expectancy -->
                <div class="formula-card">
                    <div class="formula-title">
                        <i class="fas fa-chart-bar"></i>
                        Trade Expectancy (Expected Value)
                    </div>
                    
                    <p class="formula-explanation">
                        Average amount you expect to win or lose per trade over many trades. Positive expectancy is essential for long-term profitability.
                    </p>
                    
                    <div class="formula-math">
                        E = (Win Rate × Avg Win) - (Loss Rate × Avg Loss)
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="variable-list">
                        <div class="variable-item">
                            <span class="variable-symbol">E</span>
                            <span class="variable-description">Expected value per trade</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="variable-item">
                            <span class="variable-symbol">Win Rate</span>
                            <span class="variable-description">Winning trades / total trades (as decimal)</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="variable-item">
                            <span class="variable-symbol">Avg Win</span>
                            <span class="variable-description">Average profit on winning trades</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="variable-item">
                            <span class="variable-symbol">Avg Loss</span>
                            <span class="variable-description">Average loss on losing trades (positive number)</span>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="example-box">
                        <div class="example-title">
                            <i class="fas fa-lightbulb me-2"></i>Example
                        </div>
                        <p style="color: #9ba1a6; margin-bottom: 0;">
                            55% win rate, $400 avg win, $200 avg loss:<br>
                            E = (0.55 × $400) - (0.45 × $200) = $220 - $90 = <strong style="color: #00ff88;">$130 per trade</strong>
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="verification-box">
                        <div class="verification-title">
                            <i class="fas fa-exclamation-circle"></i>
                            Sample Size Warning
                        </div>
                        <p style="color: #9ba1a6; margin-bottom: 0;">
                            Minimum 30 trades recommended for statistical significance. Results with fewer trades may not be reliable.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div style="margin-top: 1rem;">
                        <span class="reference-badge">
                            <i class="fas fa-book-open me-1"></i>
                            Van K. Tharp - Super Trader
                        </span>
                        <span class="reference-badge">
                            <i class="fas fa-calculator me-1"></i>
                            Mark Douglas - Trading in the Zone
                        </span>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Sharpe Ratio -->
                <div class="formula-card">
                    <div class="formula-title">
                        <i class="fas fa-trophy"></i>
                        Sharpe Ratio
                    </div>
                    
                    <p class="formula-explanation">
                        Risk-adjusted return measure developed by Nobel laureate William Sharpe. Measures excess return per unit of risk (volatility).
                    </p>
                    
                    <div class="formula-math">
                        Sharpe = (R - Rf) / σ
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="variable-list">
                        <div class="variable-item">
                            <span class="variable-symbol">R</span>
                            <span class="variable-description">Average return (annualized)</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="variable-item">
                            <span class="variable-symbol">Rf</span>
                            <span class="variable-description">Risk-free rate (typically 3-5% annually)</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="variable-item">
                            <span class="variable-symbol">σ</span>
                            <span class="variable-description">Standard deviation of returns (volatility)</span>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="example-box">
                        <div class="example-title">
                            <i class="fas fa-lightbulb me-2"></i>Interpretation
                        </div>
                        <p style="color: #9ba1a6; margin-bottom: 0;">
                            <strong style="color: #ff6b6b;">&lt; 1.0:</strong> Poor risk-adjusted returns<br>
                            <strong style="color: #d68b45;">1.0 - 2.0:</strong> Good risk-adjusted returns<br>
                            <strong style="color: #00ff88;">&gt; 2.0:</strong> Excellent risk-adjusted returns<br>
                            <strong style="color: #00b0ff;">&gt; 3.0:</strong> Exceptional (institutional grade)
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div style="margin-top: 1rem;">
                        <span class="reference-badge">
                            <i class="fas fa-graduation-cap me-1"></i>
                            William Sharpe - Nobel Prize (1990)
                        </span>
                        <span class="reference-badge">
                            <i class="fas fa-book-open me-1"></i>
                            Portfolio Theory & Capital Markets
                        </span>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Breakeven Calculator -->
                <div class="formula-card">
                    <div class="formula-title">
                        <i class="fas fa-balance-scale-right"></i>
                        Breakeven Win Rate
                    </div>
                    
                    <p class="formula-explanation">
                        Minimum win rate required to break even given your average win/loss ratio. Critical for evaluating if your strategy is profitable.
                    </p>
                    
                    <div class="formula-math">
                        Breakeven % = Avg Loss / (Avg Win + Avg Loss)
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="example-box">
                        <div class="example-title">
                            <i class="fas fa-lightbulb me-2"></i>Example
                        </div>
                        <p style="color: #9ba1a6; margin-bottom: 0;">
                            If avg win = $300, avg loss = $100:<br>
                            Breakeven = $100 / ($300 + $100) = <strong style="color: #00ff88;">25%</strong><br>
                            You need to win at least 25% of trades to break even.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Monte Carlo Category -->
                <h2 id="monte-carlo" class="category-header">
                    <i class="fas fa-dice me-2"></i>Monte Carlo Simulations
                </h2>

                <div class="formula-card">
                    <div class="formula-title">
                        <i class="fas fa-random"></i>
                        Monte Carlo Methodology
                    </div>
                    
                    <p class="formula-explanation">
                        We use Monte Carlo simulation to model thousands of possible future outcomes based on your trading statistics. This provides probabilistic estimates rather than deterministic predictions.
                    </p>
                    
                    <div class="verification-box">
                        <div class="verification-title">
                            <i class="fas fa-cogs"></i>
                            Implementation Details
                        </div>
                        <div style="color: #9ba1a6;">
                            <p><strong>Number of Simulations:</strong> 10,000 random paths</p>
                            <p><strong>Random Walk:</strong> Each trade outcome (win/loss) randomly selected based on your win rate</p>
                            <p><strong>Win Amount:</strong> Normally distributed around your average win (σ = 20% of mean)</p>
                            <p><strong>Loss Amount:</strong> Normally distributed around your average loss (σ = 20% of mean)</p>
                            <p style="margin-bottom: 0;"><strong>Output:</strong> Distribution of final account balances, median outcome, percentile ranges (10th, 25th, 75th, 90th)</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="example-box">
                        <div class="example-title">
                            <i class="fas fa-lightbulb me-2"></i>Why Monte Carlo?
                        </div>
                        <p style="color: #9ba1a6; margin-bottom: 0;">
                            Real trading results vary due to randomness. Monte Carlo shows the <em>range</em> of possible outcomes, not just the average. This helps you understand best-case, worst-case, and most-likely scenarios.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div style="margin-top: 1rem;">
                        <span class="reference-badge">
                            <i class="fas fa-book-open me-1"></i>
                            A Random Walk Down Wall Street (Malkiel)
                        </span>
                        <span class="reference-badge">
                            <i class="fas fa-chart-area me-1"></i>
                            Curtis Faith - Way of the Turtle
                        </span>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Growth Calculators Category -->
                <h2 id="growth" class="category-header">
                    <i class="fas fa-seedling me-2"></i>Growth Calculators
                </h2>

                <!-- Compound Growth -->
                <div class="formula-card">
                    <div class="formula-title">
                        <i class="fas fa-chart-line"></i>
                        Compound Growth Formula
                    </div>
                    
                    <p class="formula-explanation">
                        Calculate account growth with compounding returns over time. Uses geometric mean for accurate multi-period returns.
                    </p>
                    
                    <div class="formula-math">
                        Final = Initial × (1 + r)^t
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="variable-list">
                        <div class="variable-item">
                            <span class="variable-symbol">Initial</span>
                            <span class="variable-description">Starting account balance</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="variable-item">
                            <span class="variable-symbol">r</span>
                            <span class="variable-description">Average return per period (as decimal)</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="variable-item">
                            <span class="variable-symbol">t</span>
                            <span class="variable-description">Number of periods</span>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Drawdown Recovery -->
                <div class="formula-card">
                    <div class="formula-title">
                        <i class="fas fa-medkit"></i>
                        Drawdown Recovery
                    </div>
                    
                    <p class="formula-explanation">
                        Calculate the gain required to recover from a drawdown. Drawdowns are asymmetric: a 50% loss requires a 100% gain to recover.
                    </p>
                    
                    <div class="formula-math">
                        Required Gain = Drawdown / (1 - Drawdown)
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="example-box">
                        <div class="example-title">
                            <i class="fas fa-exclamation-triangle me-2"></i>Asymmetric Recovery
                        </div>
                        <p style="color: #9ba1a6; margin-bottom: 0;">
                            <strong>10% drawdown</strong> → requires <strong style="color: #00ff88;">11.1% gain</strong><br>
                            <strong>25% drawdown</strong> → requires <strong style="color: #d68b45;">33.3% gain</strong><br>
                            <strong>50% drawdown</strong> → requires <strong style="color: #ff6b6b;">100% gain</strong><br>
                            This is why risk management is critical!
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Time to Goal -->
                <div class="formula-card">
                    <div class="formula-title">
                        <i class="fas fa-clock"></i>
                        Time to Goal (Compound Interest)
                    </div>
                    
                    <p class="formula-explanation">
                        Calculate how long it takes to reach a financial goal with consistent returns and optional monthly contributions.
                    </p>
                    
                    <div class="formula-math">
                        t = ln(Goal / Initial) / ln(1 + r)
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="variable-list">
                        <div class="variable-item">
                            <span class="variable-symbol">t</span>
                            <span class="variable-description">Time periods required</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="variable-item">
